04667nam a22006255i 9780823277865DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20172018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232778657 a10.1515/97808232778652doi  a(DE-B1597)555457  a(OCoLC)1005002497  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSCI0750002bisacsh04a1942231 aCrockett, Clayton, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDerrida after the End of Writing :bPolitical Theology and New Materialism /cClayton Crockett. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. -- t1. Reading Derrida Reading Religion -- t2. Surviving Chris tian ity -- t3. Political Theology Without Sovereignty -- t4. Interrupting Heidegger with a Ram Derrida's Reading of Celan -- t5. Derrida, Lacan, and Object- Oriented Ontology -- t6. Radical Theology and the Event -- t7. Deconstructive Plasticity -- t8. Quantum Derrida -- tAfterword: The Sins of the Fathers- A Love Letter -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aWhat are we to make of Jacques Derrida's famous claim that "every other is every other," if the other could also be an object, a stone or an elementary particle? Derrida's philosophy is relevant not just for human ethical language and animality, but to profound developments in the physical and natural sciences, as well as ecology. Derrida After the End of Writing argues for the importance of reading Derrida's later work from a new materialist perspective. In conversation with Heidegger, Lacan, and Deleuze, and critically engaging newer philosophies of speculative realism and object-oriented ontology, Crockett claims that Derrida was never a linguistic idealist. Furthermore, something changes in his later philosophy something that cannot be simply described as a "turn." In Catherine Malabou's terms, there is a shift from a motor scheme of writing to a motor scheme of plasticity. Crockett explores some of the implications of interpreting Derrida through the new materialist lens of technicity or plasticity, attending to the significance of ethics, religion, and politics in his later work. By reading Derrida from a new materialist perspective, Crockett provides fresh readings of his ideas of sovereignty, religion, responsibility, and mourning. These new readings produce fruitful engagements with the thinkers who have followed Derrida, including Malabou, Timothy Morton, John D. Caputo, and Karen Barad. Here is a new reading of Derrida that moves beyond conventional understandings of poststructuralism and deconstruction, a reading that is responsive to and critical of some of the crucial developments shaping the humanities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 4aScience Studies. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aCatherine Malabou.  aJacques Derrida.  aJohn D. Caputo.  aPolitical Theology.  adeconstruction.  amaterialism.  areligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823277865?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823277865zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823277865/original  a978-3-11-072900-9 Fordham University Press Complete eB